<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Relation_to_RQ_decompositio=
n">Relation to RQ decomposition</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DQR_decomposition&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" tit=
le=3D"Edit section: Relation to RQ decomposition"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The RQ decomposition transforms a matrix <i>A</i> into the product of an=
 upper triangular matrix <i>R</i> (also known as right-triangular) and an o=
rthogonal matrix <i>Q</i>. The only difference from QR decomposition is the=
 order of these matrices.
</p><p>QR decomposition is Gram=E2=80=93Schmidt orthogonalization of column=
s of <i>A</i>, started from the first column.
</p><p>RQ decomposition is Gram=E2=80=93Schmidt orthogonalization of rows o=
f <i>A</i>, started from the last row.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Advantages_and_disadvantage=
s">Advantages and disadvantages</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DQR_decomposition&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" tit=
le=3D"Edit section: Advantages and disadvantages"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The Gram-Schmidt process is inherently numerically unstable. While the a=
pplication of the projections has an appealing geometric analogy to orthogo=
nalization, the orthogonalization itself is prone to <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerical_error" title=3D"Numerical error">numerical err=
or</a>. A significant advantage is the ease of implementation.
</p>
