<p>The matrix <i>Q</i> is orthogonal and <i>R</i> is upper triangular, so <=
span class=3D"nowrap"><i>A</i> =3D <i>QR</i></span> is the required QR deco=
mposition.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Advantages_and_disadvantage=
s_2">Advantages and disadvantages</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DQR_decomposition&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" =
title=3D"Edit section: Advantages and disadvantages"><span>edit</span></a><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The use of Householder transformations is inherently the most simple of =
the numerically stable QR decomposition algorithms due to the use of reflec=
tions as the mechanism for producing zeroes in the <i>R</i> matrix. However=
, the Householder reflection algorithm is bandwidth heavy and difficult to =
parallelize, as every reflection that produces a new zero element changes t=
he entirety of both <i>Q</i> and <i>R</i> matrices.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Parallel_implementation_of_=
Householder_QR">Parallel implementation of Householder QR</h4><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DQR_decomposition&amp;actio=
n=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Parallel implementation o=
f Householder QR"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
<p>The Householder QR method can be implemented in parallel with algorithms=
 such as the TSQR algorithm (which stands for <i>Tall Skinny QR</i>). This =
algorithm can be applied in the case when the matrix <i>A</i> has <i>m &gt;=
&gt; n</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/QR_decomposition#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
This algorithm uses a binary reduction tree to compute local householder QR=
 decomposition at each node in the forward pass, and re-constitute the Q ma=
trix in the backward pass. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bin=
ary_tree" title=3D"Binary tree">binary tree</a> structure aims at decreasin=
g the amount of communication between processor to increase performance.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Using_Givens_rotations">Usi=
ng Givens rotations</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DQR_decomposition&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit =
section: Using Givens rotations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>QR decompositions can also be computed with a series of <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Givens_rotation" title=3D"Givens rotation">Givens =
rotations</a>. Each rotation zeroes an element in the subdiagonal of the ma=
trix, forming the <i>R</i> matrix.  The concatenation of all the Givens rot=
ations forms the orthogonal <i>Q</i> matrix.
</p><p>In practice, Givens rotations are not actually performed by building=
 a whole matrix and doing a matrix multiplication.  A Givens rotation proce=
dure is used instead which does the equivalent of the sparse Givens matrix =
multiplication, without the extra work of handling the sparse elements. The=
 Givens rotation procedure is useful in situations where only relatively fe=
w off-diagonal elements need to be zeroed, and is more easily parallelized =
than <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Householder_transformation" t=
itle=3D"Householder transformation">Householder transformations</a>.
</p>
